Genus LAURUS (Tournefort) Linnc Laurus socialis Lesquercux? (Plate 7, Fig. 4)

Laurus socialis Lesquereux, Rept. U. S. Geol. Surv. Tcrr., vol. 7, 213, pl. 36, figs. 1—4, 7, 1878; Knowlton, U. S. Geol. Surv, Prof. Paper 101, 317, pl. 91, fig. 5, 1917; idem, Prof. Paper 155, 85, pl. 38, fig. 4, 1930.

There are only 3 fragmentary specimens of this type in the eolleetions. They are referred with doubt to this species. The spceimens are closely similar to those from the Raton and Denver formations, which seem 10 me, however, to differ considerably from the original type speeiinens from Evanston, Wyoming. In these the shape is more lanceolate and the seeondaries are more numerous, more obtuse, and less prominently looped near the borders. Except for their more obtuse secondaries, the leaves of L. socialis are also comparable to those of L. attaliensis Lesquercux ¹ from the Raton formation. It seems probable that at least the Denver and Medicine Bow speci- mens should be described as a new species. In the absence of better and more numerous speei- mens, however, a revision and description cannot be made at the present time.

In addition to Evanston, Raton, Denver, and Dawson occurrences reported above, Laurus socialis is found also in the Livingston formation of Montana.²

Among modern leaves the lauraceous genera appear to resemble those of Laurus socialis most closely. Several species of Persea and Laurus with similar leaf characters have been noted. Laurus nobilis Linne, for example, has leaves of essentially similar shape and venation. An even closer comparison may be noted in the leaves of Persea cardinensis (L.) Nees.³ A general re- semblance is also apparent with leaves of M aqnolia (Magnoliaceae) and Diospyros (Ebenaceae).
